Firstly, this is NOT MY IDEA! It was published by Vik Olliver, Diamond Age Solutions Ltd. http://diamondage.co.nz. I have reproduced it here, assuming that it is public domain. However, I will be happy to remove it if the original author would like me to. His document says "Documentation released under the GFDL for free reproduction." I hope that extends to his pictures! I am building a mrkimrobotics 1X2 reprap http://mrkimrobotics.com/ and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5773 from basic, locally sourced parts, and getting to the point were I need to create a hot end. I realised I needed a lathe for this, but don't have space or cash for a real one and all thingiverse lathes http://www.thingiverse.com/tag:lathe require some reprapped parts - but mine isn't built yet! Somehow I stumbled upon Vik's page and feel it deserves a wider audience. I built mine using a Bosch hand drill with handle adapter clamped in a Black and Decker Workmate for one end, and the chuck from my drill press G-clamped to a small vice for the other. I have only been playing around with this so far, and haven't got this working quite well enough yet to make a hot end, but it has excellent potential. Vik Olliver: "Why an 'Afghan Lathe'? Because I first saw this kind of technique being used by Afghan gunsmiths to produce counterfeit firearms with remarkable precision."

Full instructions at:
http://staff.bath.ac.uk/ensab/replicator/Downloads/Afghan_lathe/Afghan_Lathe.html Blog post by Vik at:
http://blog.reprap.org/2005/07/afghan-lathe-technique-updated.html
As you can see the idea is quite old, but very effective none the less! PDF (same as 1st link web page; referred to in above blog post) at:
http://diamondage.co.nz/research_docs/Afghan_Lathe.pdf Update
I finally got around to drilling out a 55mm brass bolt for the hot end of my repstrap. With the tools I had, I couldn't quite get this to work like Vik's instructions, mainly because I didn't have a decent vice. Instead, I used a bench drill press and, for the second chuck, removed the chuck and drive shaft from an old hand power drill. This slotted into the drill press bed central hole and I drilled a wooden block to hold it underneath. Couple of problems: The wooden block couldn't hold the second chuck still for very long, but this wasn't too much of a problem. The drill self-centred on the work, and I could hold it with my hand, or when the hole got very deep with some large grips, to keep it flat on the bed. The second problem was that my drill press chuck runs slightly eccentrically (about 0.5mm), and I occasionally took out the work to check it. Each time I put it back into the chuck, it wasn't always in the same place, so the hole then ran eccentrically. This caused a lot of binding on the drill before I worked out what was going on! Make sure the work goes back in the chuck in same place. Finally, though brass is pretty easy to work, sharp drills always help. I drilled it out at 3mm first (the smallest drill that would go all the way through), then 4mm. Update 2
I bought a cheap engineer's/bench drill vice (Â£11), drilled a hole in a wooden block slightly smaller than the 'tail stock' chuck, cut the wooden block length ways through the centre of the hole. This acts as a clamp to hold the tail stock chuck in the vice which is clamped to the drill table, it is adjustable in more directions than the drill table, and is generally a lot more secure and safer than holding the chuck by hand!

The Nabi Jr is a $100 Android tablet designed for toddlers -- a really great product (especially after a few additions in "Daddy Mode"). However, the accessory stands for it are not all that cheap and, frankly, have hinges that are not very toddler friendly. This is a solid one-piece stand that simply slips firmly over any of the mounting squares on the back -- allowing the Nabi Jr to sit nicely in many orientations and angles. Our 2-year-old "test subject" also found it to be a good handle for carrying the unit while watching it.  
My first design, shown printed in black PLA, worked nicely but had a rounded edge with a little too much overhang to print smoothly. My second design, shown in white and posted here as an STL, has 45-degree beveled edges instead, and prints very nicely.

The white PLA print was made with 0.25mm and 25% fill, printed slightly hot to ensure good fusing. It took about 3/4 hour to print on our MakerGear M2. It is about as close to toddler-proof as I can imagine.

description.text:
Hello world! I proudly release my circulating air incubator. The "base" version comes with two slots and a room of 124x124x84mm and can be extended up to four slots and 124x124x168mm (length x width x height).
Each slot can hold two petri dishes, or you just insert the lower tray and can put some test-tubes on it.
The temperature can be set in 1°C steps. You need the following additional parts to build the incubator:
  • Metal plate 120x120x1mm
  • Digital Thermostat: http://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B00H3ZN3IQ
  • Power Supply: http://www.amazon.de/dp/B0089LFGIS
  • DC Connector: http://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B00CI6IOCA
  • Power Switch: http://www.amazon.de/dp/B00KGZBJFO
  • Heater: http://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B004W7H2YO
  • Radial fan: http://www.amazon.de/dp/B00BJMWKGU
  • PWM Module (optional if you want to regulate the fan speed, I recommend it): http://www.amazon.de/gp/product/B00CWSO2IY
  • some M4x16 screws and nuts
  • glue
  • soldering iron and some wires
    • Of course you do not need to buy it from Amazon, but I think it is the easiest way to show you which parts are working.

I named the parts by _abs and _pla. The _abs-parts should really be printed with ABS or any other filament, that is not as temperatur critically as it is PLA. All parts with the _abs suffix will get as warm as you set it on the thermostat. Of course, you can print the _pla-parts with ABS, too. You need these parts in any case:
  • 1_groundplate_pla
  • 2_backplate_pla
  • 3_frontplate_abs
  • 4_midplate_abs
  • 5_heatplate_bottom_abs
  • 2x 6_slot_abs
  • 2x 7_tray_abs
  • 8_case_bottom_pla
  • 10_case_top_pla
  • 11_lid_abs
  • 14_top_lid_pla
  • 21_small_parts (contains 12_fan_lid_abs, 13_fan_holder_abs, 15_door_hinge_pla, 16_door_knob_abs, 20_door_latch_pla)
    • For a 2-slot version (84mm inner height):
  • 17_door_for_2_trays_abs
    • For a 3-slot version (126mm inner height):
  • 18_door_for_3_trays_abs
  • 9_case_spacer_pla
  • one additional 6_slot_abs
  • one additional 7_tray_abs
    • For a 4-slot version (168mm inner height):
  • 19_door_for_4_trays_abs
  • 2x 9_case_spacer_pla
  • two additional 6_slot_abs
  • two additional 7_tray_abs
    • Start glueing the 6_slot on each other. I'm working on a screwed version, but it will take some time. Be careful that the funnel at the back fits to the next slot. Glue your slots on 4_midplate, again be careful with the funnel.
    Take one of 15_door_hinge (part of 21_small_parts) and glue it to 4_midplate. Take the other hinge and glue it to 11_lid (check out the photos!). Glue 16_door_knob into the whole of your door (it should look outside at the end :P )
    Last thing to glue: 12_fan_lid, glue it on the open funnel on 11_lid. Do not forget to insert the temperature sensor of controller to the funnel first (the small gap at the top of the funnel is for the cable).
    No more glueing, now we need M4 screws & nuts. I heated the M4 nuts a bit, so they fit perfectly in the placeholders. Check out the build-photos, you can see where every part has its place. If you use the PWM to control your fan you should never go under 50% or even stop it. It would damage at least the heatplate-holder. You can put small styropor-pellets in the gap between the outer case and the slots. That reduces heat loss.

Some times creation is all about low hanging fruit. I already have a Rotary Stewart Platform (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:64396) and I suck at Kerbal Space Program. I thought if I could make a 6DOF joystick maybe I could do better at orbital rendezvous. It could also work in Minecraft or Descent, maybe.
If you use one of my designs, please let me know! I'd love to see what you make with it and share with others who are interested.
It would be awesome if someone would help improve the kinematics for this robot. Forward kinematics are beyond my math skills and they're essential to make the joystick complete.

• get the code from github.com/MarginallyClever/RotaryStewartPlatform/
  • get the parts kit from bit.ly/ZO0Dec or laser cut this design. You'll need two frames, one end effector1, and three end effector 2.
  • get three TAMIYA 70171 kits. Cut the M3 rods in half.
  • modify the servos: remove the pcbs and wire the potentiometer directly to the cable.
  • assemble as you see in the pictures. You'll have one extra end effector plate when you're done. Use the extra M3 rods to sandwich the two frame plates together, securing the servos in place.
  • upload firmware
  • drive one stewart platform from another

All the reds go to 5v. All the blacks go to GND. All the left servos have been modified to be just potentiometers, and they go to analog pins 0-5. The right are normal potentiometers and they go to digital pins with PWM. Then it's a 1:1. You could also record the values to an SD card and play it later, or send them over the web... that parts kinda boring for me, so I didn't bother.
There are also 4-wire servos (adafruit?) that will let you record and playback on the same servo.

description.text: This is a simple adapter to connect build a spool out of standard European 50mm plastic sewage pipe and some 608 skate bearings. Both the bearings and the pipe are press fit when printed on our Thing-O-Matic. I used a M8 bolt through the bearing as an axle. It doesn't really work, the diameter is too small for the loose plastic filament. When pulled the strand under tension cuts through the stack of filaments and ends up at the bottom. Presumably re-spoling might help, need to test it. Also need to make another version for larger diameter pipe. That said, this system beats our old system of storing the filament in a box on the table.. :-) This part was made with Tinkercad. Edit the part online at: https://tinkercad.com/p/acc032818bbe0f42

Print out 2 pieces of the coupler. Press fit the 608 skate bearings. Tighten the M8 bolt and nut, the bolt head should be on the side of the bearing with the end sticking out. Press fit the coupler to the sewage pipe, add some glue to hold it in place. Add sides guides made from cardboard. Hang above your printer using wire or string.

title: Mini Kossel doubled frame top vertex - for 1515 extrusion

description.text: I built a larger version of the Mini Kossel and found the frame would wiggle a bit when printing fast. The bottom corner mounts were already nice and tall because they also held the stepper motors but the top corner pieces were pretty small and had only one mounting bolt on the vertical extrusion.  So I customized the original frame_top part to create a doubled size part and still have space under it for the end stop switch mount.

Print the default part just 5mm or so high and stop the print so you can test the fit on your extrusions. Remember to clean off the bottom layer brim on the inside hole. The fit should be tight. I like it so tight that for final assembly I have to warm the part and the extrusion end with a heat gun and bang on the other end of the extrusion to get it on. I put the part on a piece of wood the floor(level) then line up the extrusion on the part(straight up) and then knock the extrusion through the part. I then slide the part on the hot end of the extrusion a few times before moving it to the cool end of the extrusion. When all cooled, it should slide very tightly off the extrusion. Adjust the tolerance_frame_dmk if your extrusion fits too loose or too tight.

Im missing a Bowden extruder which looks good! So I have been rethinking it: It might work or it might not! - Its a work in progress. I have created a new version where the extruder are made of 3 parts:
  • The inner chassis which You se on the Photo
  • Body Front - planned - much like version 1
  • Body Back - planned - much like version 1
    • The philosophy is that You can use the Chassis - which I make in 2 versions - one with fixed hotend holder and one with replaceable hotend holder! - And then draw Your own body which fits Your needs for a certain fan/fans and hot end! The 3 last pictures shows how the gliders hold the extruder and how You start mounting it on the lowest glider and then tilt it and press it under the top rod, and then press the gliders into it! Its created for E3D v6, by the way!
    Please work with me on this! (o:
    It would be great with autolevel build in - in a slightly larger body - Im thinking - a vertical moving sensor instead of the turning version..
    60 og 70 mm fans might also be possible!.

Slightly modified the OpenSCAD file as I wasn't happy with the way the gear teeth intersected the cube - the 'horns' on the large gears in the original were very fragile and didn't look great.
This involved changing the gear teeth counts (from 18/9 to 18/12) and adding a 'rotation_tweak' parameter to the code that lets you adjust the rotation of the gears, so adding 5 degrees (half a tooth) moved the 'horns' from the large gear to the small ones.
As I don't have MatLab, I rewrote the gearopt.m script in perl, it's below as gearopt.pl

description.text:
I was having trouble printing the Nuttraps in a way that I could easily align the nuts within them. I could get them in but couldn't remove them to align them, so I redesigned them to have open slots. I also redesigned the Z Axis Top Left as the hole in the original file that accepts the 625 bearing is 16.75mm, the OD of a 625 bearing is only 16mm. I then mirrored the Left hand part in repetier to use on the right hand side as I don't need the Bowden tube holder on the original Right hand part.

description.text:
This is functional copy of a sycamore seed. It really flies!  
Have you ever wanted to find the perfect one that flies the best? This is your chance to design it. And the best thing, once you have found the right design you can always print another when it blows away.

The construction for this was inspired by the PaperFly. It worked very nicely for me first try. I just taped a bit of tissue paper across by build platform and printed. Trimmed with scissors and it worked. The outing of the wing was designed in Inkscape, the leading edge is on the "spine" layer and will be printed thicker than the trailing edge on the "veins" layer. The 3D build up was done with OpenSCAD. The seed is pure OpenSCAD, the rest is extruded from the DXF. Getting your work from Inkscape into OpenSCAD is a bit tricky see;http://repraprip.blogspot.co.nz/2011/05/inkscape-to-openscad-dxf-tutorial.html Or try: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:25036 (haven't tried it yet but it looks good). This is my first try, it flies but I know I could do a lot better. At a different stage of life this could have made the basis of an honors project. Please post your best design!
